---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Eight parties, five behaviours · Riksdag Revealed"
  description="The 2022-26 Riksdag mandate read by behaviour. On the chamber record, the eight parties on the 2026 ballot resolve into five behavioural clusters, with the four-party Tidö bloc forming during the mandate itself. Roll-call votes, reservations, speeches and manifestos as evidence."
>
  <article class="container">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Riksdag Revealed · The 2022-26 mandate</p>
      <h1>Eight parties, five behaviours</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Sweden has eight parties on the 2026 ballot. On the chamber
        record of the 2022-26 mandate they group into five behavioural
        clusters, one of which, the four-party Tidö bloc, took shape
        during the mandate itself.
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      When voters compare parties they reach for familiar shortcuts: a
      left-right slider, an alliance label, a coalition map. Each of
      these assumes that the eight parties on the 2026 ballot still
      mean what they meant in 2022. The parliamentary record of the
      mandate gives reason to question that assumption.
    </p>

    <p>
      The central claim of this article can be stated in one sentence.
      On the chamber record of the 2022-26 mandate, the eight parties
      on the 2026 ballot resolve into five behavioural clusters:
    </p>

    <ul class="entity-list">
      <li><strong>The Tidö bloc.</strong> M, KD, L and SD, voting and
      reasoning together as one. The fusion took place during the
      mandate, and it was asymmetric: SD moved toward the cabinet,
      and M's vocabulary moved toward SD.</li>
      <li><strong>Socialdemokraterna.</strong> Separate in voting
      behaviour from the other opposition parties as well as from the
      cabinet, occupying its own arm of the chamber map.</li>
      <li><strong>V and MP together.</strong> The only opposition pair
      that is close on both vote-stance similarity and
      reservation-reasoning similarity, indicating a genuine bloc
      rather than a coalition of arithmetic.</li>
      <li><strong>Centerpartiet, behaviourally on the opposition
      side.</strong> Nominally at the centre of Swedish politics, but
      voting with Socialdemokraterna on 91 % of chamber votes during
      the mandate and clustering with V and MP on the chamber map.</li>
      <li><strong>The Liberalerna defectors.</strong> Eight of the
      twelve MPs with the highest defection ratio in the Riksdag are
      members of Liberalerna whose voting records sit closer to KD or
      M than to L. The L caucus is, in voting behaviour, substantially
      inside the KD and M clusters.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The article first walks through the five clusters at party-mean
      level, then turns to how the Tidö cluster formed during the
      mandate, then reads the eight 2022 manifestos to see where the
      parties still differ on paper, and finally holds the two layers
      against each other. The underlying data consists of some two and
      a half thousand chamber votes, eleven thousand written
      reservations, fifty thousand chamber speeches, and the eight
      2022 manifestos.
    </p>

    <h2>The chamber map</h2>

    <p>
      The behavioural map is built by projecting every chamber vote of
      the mandate, member by member, into two dimensions through PCA
      on the 424-by-2,501 vote matrix.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/01_behavioural_map.png`} alt="Behavioural map of the Riksdag based on voting patterns, 2022-2026" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The Riksdag 2022-2026, projected into two dimensions via PCA on
        the voting matrix. The first axis (PC1, 46 % of variance)
        separates the Tidö government bloc from the opposition. The
        second (PC2, 13.5 %) splits the opposition into a
        Socialdemokrat arm and a V/MP/C arm. Centerpartiet sits at the
        centre of the first axis but well down on the second:
        geographically centrist, behaviourally close to the soft left.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Four of the five clusters are visible at party-mean level on
      this map:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Tidö</strong>: M, KD, L and SD, packed tightly on
      the right of PC1.</li>
      <li><strong>S</strong>: alone on the upper left, in its own arm
      of PC2.</li>
      <li><strong>V and MP</strong>: together on the lower diagonal,
      with V furthest from the centre on the bloc axis.</li>
      <li><strong>C</strong>: at the centre of PC1 but well down PC2,
      sitting with V and MP rather than between cabinet and
      opposition.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Equally informative is what is not on the map. No coalition cuts
      across the cabinet and opposition line, and there is no
      realignment of Centerpartiet onto the cabinet side. The
      within-opposition split on PC2 is real, in the sense that
      Socialdemokraterna sits clearly apart from V, MP and C, and that
      separation is what makes the second axis worth 13 % of variance.
      The split nevertheless stays on the opposition side of the bloc
      line.
    </p>

    <p>
      For Centerpartiet voters the practical implication is that the
      party's behavioural position lies on the opposition side of the
      bloc line rather than in the centre of it. C sits at the centre
      of PC1 but in the V and MP arm of PC2, and across the mandate
      voted with Socialdemokraterna on 91 % of chamber votes.
    </p>

    <h3>The same pattern, per topic</h3>

    <p>
      The cluster pattern is not an artefact of a single PCA. The
      same alignment recurs across substantively different policy
      topics, as the next figure shows.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/33_per_topic_stance.png`} alt="Vote stance per party per topic, top 20 by cross-party variance" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mean vote stance per (party, topic). +1 = the party consistently
        voted Yes on points classified into that topic, -1 = consistently
        No, 0 = mixed. Topics are sorted left-to-right by cross-party
        variance, so the most polarising appear first.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Migration is the most differentiating topic by a clear margin,
      followed by international aid, pharmaceuticals and dental care,
      climate, and schools. In each of these the alignment recurs:
      V, MP and C on one side, M, KD, L and SD on the other, with
      Socialdemokraterna in between.
    </p>

    <h3>Vote and reasoning</h3>

    <p>
      Voting together is not the same as reasoning together. For
      every party pair we measure two similarities: a vote-stance
      similarity from the chamber record, and a reasoning similarity
      taken as the topic-centred cosine between reservation
      reasoning vectors. The two correlate at roughly r = 0.55, and
      the off-trend pairs are the most informative.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/34_vote_vs_reasoning.png`} alt="Party pair vote similarity vs reasoning similarity" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Each point is one of the 28 party pairs. X axis: similarity of
        how the two parties voted across all 2,501 chamber votes.
        Y axis: similarity of how the two parties reasoned in their
        reservations and majority opinions, with the parliamentary
        average per topic subtracted. The dashed line is the cross-pair
        trend. Pairs above the line argue more alike than they vote.
        Pairs below vote together but reason apart.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Three pairs are worth examining. Each one confirms or qualifies
      one of the five clusters identified above.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>V and MP: vote alike and argue alike.</strong> The
        only opposition pair that sits above the cross-pair trend on
        reasoning similarity, which confirms the V and MP cluster at
        the reasoning layer as well as on the vote record.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>M and SD: vote alike, argue apart.</strong> Vote
        similarity 0.84, but reasoning similarity sits well below
        the cross-pair trend line. The same below-trend pattern
        holds for L-SD and KD-SD. The four Tidö parties vote as a
        bloc on the chamber floor, but Sverigedemokraterna's
        parliamentary reasoning text sits closer to the opposition
        parties' reasoning text than to its cabinet partners'.
        Sverigedemokraterna votes with the cabinet, and writes in
        opposition register.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>S and C: vote alike, argue apart.</strong>
        Socialdemokraterna and Centerpartiet vote together 91 % of
        the time, more than any other non-cabinet pair, but they sit
        substantially below the reasoning trend. They share
        opposition arithmetic without sharing the underlying values
        vocabulary, which is why they do not form a sixth cluster.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Four of the five clusters are now established at party-mean
      level. The fifth, the Liberalerna defectors, only emerges once
      the analysis moves below party averages. The next section
      reaches that level of detail after first tracing how the Tidö
      cluster formed during the mandate.
    </p>

    <h2>How four parties became one</h2>

    <p>
      The party positions shown on the chamber map are mean positions
      across the whole mandate. The way those mean positions came
      about, in particular for the four parties that make up the Tidö
      bloc, is the subject of this section.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/07_tido_collapse.png`} alt="The Tidö bloc collapsing into a single cluster" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The four parties of the Tidö bloc (M, KD, L and SD as a
        support party), per parliamentary year. The mean pairwise
        distance between their centroids falls from 9.08 in 2022/23 to
        0.43 in 2025/26. By the election year the four points sit on
        top of one another.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Since the cabinet trio has by definition voted as a unit, the
      collapse must reflect Sverigedemokraterna moving toward the
      cabinet's positions rather than the cabinet adjusting toward
      SD. The movement also accelerated as the election approached.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/08_agreement_trend.png`} alt="Tidö bloc agreement trend over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left panel.</strong> Share of chamber votes where the
        entire Tidö bloc voted unanimously. The share rose from 73 %
        in 2024/25 to 98 % in 2025/26, in step with the start of the
        election year.
        <strong>Right panel.</strong> The rise is driven entirely by
        SD aligning with the cabinet's positions, not the cabinet
        adjusting toward SD.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Of the 687 chamber votes held in 2025/26, Sverigedemokraterna
      deviated from the cabinet's position on eleven.
    </p>

    <p class="pullquote">
      SD's filed reservations fell from 574 in 2024/25 to 17 in
      2025/26. In the election year, Sverigedemokraterna effectively
      ceased to file the kind of dissenting parliamentary documents
      that characterise an opposition party.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/21_sd_reservation_collapse.png`} alt="SD reservations per parliamentary year, the election-year collapse" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Reservations filed per party and parliamentary year. The thick
        yellow line is SD: 749, 402, 574, 17. The opposition parties
        rise or hold steady. The cabinet parties (M, KD, L) are
        excluded as, being the majority, they file very few.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>Vote alignment without joint authorship</h3>

    <p>
      The vote convergence preceded the reservation collapse. For most
      of the mandate, Sverigedemokraterna voted alongside the cabinet
      without co-signing the cabinet's alternative proposals.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/30_temporal_coauthorship.png`} alt="Reservation co-authorship over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left.</strong> Opposition parties co-sign reservations
        with each other continuously, with V-MP the tightest pair (0.26
        to 0.37). All three pairs tick up in 2025/26, the election year,
        as opposition activity intensifies.
        <strong>Right.</strong> SD with the three cabinet parties:
        co-authorship is structurally zero for the first three years.
        In the election year a single uptick: KD-SD rises to 0.24,
        while M-SD and L-SD remain flat. The first co-signed
        reservations between SD and a cabinet party appear only when
        the election is six months away.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Across the entire mandate, SD has co-signed exactly three
      reservations with a cabinet party (all of them with KD), out of
      nearly eleven thousand reservations filed in total. SD has voted
      with the cabinet on 78 % of chamber votes across the mandate,
      rising to 98 % in the election year, but the joint signing of
      alternative proposals only began in the last six months before
      the election. For three years, SD voted alongside the cabinet
      without co-authoring its dissenting documents.
    </p>

    <p>
      The implication for a voter depends on which register matters
      more. Measured in votes, SD has functioned as a cabinet party
      throughout the mandate. Measured in joint authorship of
      dissenting proposals, SD was separate from the cabinet for
      three years and aligned only in the final stretch before the
      election.
    </p>

    <h3>M and SD: shared votes, separate reasoning registers</h3>

    <p>
      M and SD voted alike during the mandate and produced the same
      chamber outcomes, but their parliamentary reasoning texts did
      not converge in the same way the vote pattern did. Moderaterna
      writes in administrative-procedural language; Sverigedemokraterna
      writes in outcome-oriented language; the two registers do not
      blend even where the vote outcomes coincide. The Tidö bloc is
      a vote bloc on the parliamentary record. It is not a reasoning
      bloc.
    </p>

    <h3>The fifth cluster: the L defectors</h3>

    <p>
      Party-mean positions can conceal substantial variation between
      individual MPs. For each MP we compute the ratio of the
      distance to that MP's own party centroid against the distance
      to the nearest other party's centroid. A ratio above 1
      indicates that the MP's voting record sits closer to another
      party than to their own.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/31_defectors.png`} alt="Top behavioural defectors over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The 12 MPs with the highest distance-to-own-party /
        distance-to-nearest-other-party ratio, on a log scale. The
        dashed line marks equidistance. A ratio of 5x means the MP is
        five times further from their own party's centroid than from
        another party's.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Eight of the twelve MPs with the highest defection ratio are
      members of Liberalerna whose voting records sit closer to KD or
      M than to L. The collapse observed at party-mean level is
      therefore also visible at the level of individual MPs: a
      substantial share of the L caucus is, in voting behaviour, not
      readily distinguishable from KD or M members. This is the fifth
      cluster: an L caucus that votes the cabinet's positions on the
      floor, even when Liberalerna is the formal author of the
      proposal.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/28_centroid_trajectories.png`} alt="Each party's voting centroid drift across four parliamentary years" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Each party's voting centroid across the four parliamentary
        years. Dot size grows with year. The arrow on the last segment
        points to where the party landed in the election year. Beyond
        the Tidö story, MP drifted up PC2, V drifted further from the
        centre on PC1, and S barely moved at all.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      For a 2026 voter, the practical consequence is that the four
      Tidö parties on the ballot are, on the parliamentary record of
      this mandate, behaviourally not distinguishable from one
      another. A vote cast for any of the four amounts to support
      for the same set of outcomes.
    </p>

    <h2>The manifesto layer: where the eight are still eight</h2>

    <p>
      Voted behaviour collapses the eight parties into five clusters;
      manifesto text does not. Read as documents, the eight 2022
      manifestos remain eight separate texts. They are, however, not
      symmetrical in length, scope or coverage, and that asymmetry
      matters before any cross-party comparison.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/36_manifesto_coverage.png`} alt="Manifesto topical coverage per party" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left.</strong> Sentence count per (party, topic) for the
        eight 2022 manifestos, after assigning each sentence to its
        nearest of 28 policy topics. Topics are ordered left to right by
        total coverage across parties.
        <strong>Right.</strong> Number of topics where the party has at
        least five on-topic manifesto sentences. SD covers 19 of 28
        topics; KD covers 1.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      SD's 21,000-word manifesto registers meaningful content in 19 of
      the 28 policy topics, while KD's 1,600-word manifesto covers
      one. Any cross-party manifesto comparison is therefore sensitive
      to which topics each party chose to write about. With that
      caveat in place, the manifestos can be read along four
      dimensions: diagnosis (what is wrong), end state (what should
      be), mechanism (how to get there), and the values behind the
      answers.
    </p>

    <h3>Diagnosis: what is wrong with Sweden</h3>

    <p>
      Two parties are notably diagnosis-heavy.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Sverigedemokraterna.</strong> 12.8 % of substantive
        sentences are problem statements, by some margin the largest
        share of the eight. The diagnoses concern crime, migration
        costs, and cultural fragmentation.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Kristdemokraterna.</strong> 10.9 % of substantive
        sentences are diagnostic, despite the manifesto being the
        shortest of the eight (1.6k words in total). Measured per
        word, KD is the most concerned with what is wrong. The
        diagnoses concern family fragility, mental health, and
        weakened community.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      At the other end of the scale, Centerpartiet is the most
      forward-looking (4.7 % diagnosis): a manifesto light on
      critique and heavy on policy detail. Vänsterpartiet diagnoses
      inequality and exploitation (9.9 %), and Moderaterna diagnoses
      weak state institutions and the lack of consequences (7.5 %).
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_diagnosis.png`} alt="Diagnosis similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Cosine similarity between the party-level mean embedding of all
        diagnosis sentences. SD and KD share the language of crisis
        most strongly. V and MP cluster on inequality and climate
        framing. The cabinet trio (M, KD, L) does not cluster on
        diagnosis as cleanly as it does on the vote record, because
        the three parties describe different problems even when they
        end up voting for the same solutions.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      One pattern in the diagnosis matrix foreshadows the chamber
      story. Sverigedemokraterna and Moderaterna describe Sweden's
      problems in more similar language than M and L do, despite M
      and L sharing a cabinet. The vote-and-reasoning fusion that
      would later appear on the floor was already visible in the
      diagnostic vocabulary of the 2022 manifestos.
    </p>

    <h3>End state: what should Sweden be</h3>

    <p>
      End-state sentences are the aspirational core of a manifesto:
      "we want a Sweden where ...", "every child should ...", "a
      society in which ...". The share differs by almost a factor of
      six between the most and least vision-heavy manifestos.
    </p>

    <table class="data-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Party</th><th>End-state share</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>MP</td><td>17.0 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C</td><td>10.5 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>L</td><td>10.4 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>V</td><td>7.9 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>S</td><td>7.5 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>M</td><td>6.2 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>SD</td><td>5.7 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>KD</td><td>3.1 %</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>
      Miljöpartiet is unusually structured around vision, with nearly
      one in five sentences describing a future to aspire to.
      Kristdemokraterna is the opposite, with a short manifesto built
      almost entirely from critique and very thin description of
      what should replace it. Sverigedemokraterna lands near the
      bottom of the table as well, which is consistent with the
      diagnosis-heavy reading: a manifesto more invested in naming
      what has gone wrong than in describing what should replace it.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_end_state.png`} alt="End-state similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        End-state language similarity. The pattern flattens. Most
        parties land at 0.78 to 0.90 with one another. The aspirational
        vocabulary of Swedish politics ("trygghet för alla", "ett
        starkt Sverige", "en hållbar framtid") is broadly shared, even
        between parties who agree on almost nothing else.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      End-state similarity is a poor discriminator between parties.
      When two manifestos describe the future Sweden they want in
      similar words, that says little about whether they propose to
      arrive at that future in similar ways. The more substantive
      differences sit in the diagnosis and mechanism layers rather
      than in the end state.
    </p>

    <h3>Mechanism: by what means</h3>

    <p>
      Mechanism is the most concrete and the most differentiated of
      the four dimensions. Moderaterna's manifesto is the most
      mechanism-heavy of the eight, with 20.5 % of substantive
      sentences in that register. A fifth of its content takes the
      form of proposals using verbs such as <em>höja</em>,
      <em>skärpa</em>, <em>reformera</em>, <em>införa</em>. The
      cabinet's policy register is built into the manifesto.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_mechanism.png`} alt="Mechanism similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mechanism-language similarity. M, KD and L cluster as expected,
        the cabinet's shared register. C and L cluster slightly
        separately, with a tilt toward market vocabulary. SD sits
        somewhat apart from M, KD, L despite voting almost identically
        with them on the floor.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The cabinet trio and SD vote identically but describe their
      mechanisms using different vocabulary. M, KD and L employ
      administrative and procedural language (<em>reformera</em>,
      <em>tilldela</em>, <em>tillsyn</em>), while SD uses
      outcome-oriented language (<em>Sverige måste</em>,
      <em>det räcker nu</em>, <em>vi ska vända utvecklingen</em>).
      The proposals frequently coincide in substance even where the
      manifestos describe them in dissimilar terms.
    </p>

    <p>
      Mechanism preferences also drift inside parliament. We score
      each chamber speech on four mechanism axes, each defined by a
      short curated word list: market versus regulation, prevention
      versus punishment, central state versus local, and universal
      versus targeted welfare. The score on each axis is the
      relative frequency of the two vocabularies.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/29_temporal_how_lexicon.png`} alt="Mechanism vocabulary per party over four parliamentary years" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Four mechanism axes, per party, per parliamentary year. Each
        line is one party's relative frequency of the two vocabularies
        on that axis.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Two patterns stand out.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>The prevention-punishment axis swung sharply.</strong>
        Centerpartiet and Miljöpartiet both moved 0.28 to 0.30 units
        toward punishment vocabulary across the mandate. These are
        the two parties one might least expect to shift in this
        direction. The Tidö parties, which already used more
        punishment vocabulary at the start, moved less. The
        opposition adopted the framing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Moderaterna's market vocabulary grew (+0.16) while
        Liberalerna's shrank (-0.11).</strong> The cabinet's two
        ostensibly market-friendly parties moved in opposite
        directions on the market-regulation axis. M's market
        register rose, while L's fell as Liberalerna's chamber
        speech took on a more administrative vocabulary.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Considered as a forecast, the directional drift matters more
      than the absolute positions. The C and MP that voters chose in
      2022 used less punishment vocabulary than the C and MP that
      appear on the 2026 ballot. Vocabulary shifts do not constitute
      policy commitments, but they are early indicators of where
      each party's centre of gravity is moving.
    </p>

    <h3>Values: signature vocabularies</h3>

    <p>
      Each manifesto invokes a recognisable set of values. Some are
      widely shared (frihet, demokrati), while others belong
      distinctively to one or two parties.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/22_manifesto_values.png`} alt="Value frequency heatmap" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-1000-word frequency of value vocabulary across the eight
        2022 manifestos, z-scored across parties. Red = invokes that
        value more than average; blue = less. Values are sorted
        left-to-right by how distinctively one party owns them.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The signature values come through cleanly:
    </p>

    <ul class="signature-values">
      <li><strong>M</strong> · ordning (+2.2 σ). No other value
        distinguishes M as strongly. The Moderate manifesto is built
        around the lack-of-order diagnosis.</li>
      <li><strong>KD</strong> · trygghet (+2.1 σ), ansvar (+1.6 σ),
        staten (+1.4 σ). A statist-conservative cluster, the most
        distinct of all eight.</li>
      <li><strong>C</strong> · jämställdhet (+2.0 σ), marknaden
        (+1.8 σ), individens (+1.6 σ). Liberal in the European sense,
        wholly different from KD despite sitting in the same camp.</li>
      <li><strong>MP</strong> · rättvisa (+2.0 σ), klimat (+1.9 σ),
        solidaritet (+1.2 σ). MP and V share a value vocabulary, and
        on climate MP stands alone.</li>
      <li><strong>L</strong> · frihet (+1.7 σ), valfrihet (+1.7 σ),
        demokrati (+1.6 σ). Classical liberal, with a value vocabulary
        closer to C than to KD even though L sits in the cabinet
        with KD.</li>
      <li><strong>SD</strong> · nationell identitet (+1.8 σ),
        tradition (+1.4 σ), staten (+1.2 σ). The most predictable
        profile in the table.</li>
      <li><strong>V</strong> · jämlikhet (+1.7 σ), solidaritet
        (+1.6 σ), kollektivets (+1.5 σ). Class-based vocabulary,
        also predictable.</li>
      <li><strong>S</strong> · tradition (+1.8 σ), öppenhet (+1.6 σ),
        kollektivets (+1.6 σ). The surprise of the table.
        Socialdemokraterna invoke "tradition" more frequently per
        word than Sverigedemokraterna do. The vocabulary of the
        folkhem reads as traditional when measured.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The pairings are coherent. V and S share the kollektivets
      register; C and L share the marknaden and valfrihet register;
      SD and KD share the trygghet, staten and tradition register.
      Miljöpartiet stands alone on klimat. The hardest party to
      summarise in a single value is Moderaterna, whose value
      vocabulary is sparse compared to the others, and whose
      manifesto reads as mechanism-first and value-second.
    </p>

    <h3>Coherence: do the four layers fit together?</h3>

    <p>
      Diagnosis, end state, mechanism and values are separable as
      analytical dimensions. Whether they are coherent inside a
      given manifesto is an empirical question. For each party we
      compute the mean SBERT embedding of all diagnosis sentences,
      all end-state sentences and all mechanism sentences, and then
      take cosine similarity between each pair of mean embeddings.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/38_party_coherence.png`} alt="Within-party cosine between element vectors" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        For each party, pairwise cosine between the mean embedding of
        their diagnosis sentences, end-state sentences, and mechanism
        sentences. Higher means the three element vocabularies look
        more alike. KD is excluded for having too few end-state
        sentences (n=4).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Two patterns are visible within an otherwise narrow range of
      values.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>End-state and mechanism are always closer to each
        other than either is to diagnosis.</strong> For every party,
        the green bar is taller than the orange bar. The language of
        "what we want" and the language of "what we will do" share
        vocabulary in a way that the language of "what is wrong"
        does not. This is a structural pattern of Swedish political
        writing rather than a feature of any particular party.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>SD has the highest internal coherence (mean 0.86)
        and MP has the lowest (0.78).</strong> SD's long, technical
        manifesto reads as one document about one subject. MP's
        manifesto sits across more vocabularies (climate language,
        rights language, mechanism language) that overlap less. The
        cross-party spread is small but consistent, in the sense
        that parties with longer, single-author manifestos read as
        more internally coherent than those that read like
        compilations.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The gap: stated and revealed</h2>

    <p>
      The two layers offer two readings of the same eight parties.
      The voted record collapses them into five clusters, while the
      manifestos keep them at eight. The natural follow-up question
      is therefore how well each party's 2022 manifesto still
      describes its 2022-26 parliamentary work.
    </p>

    <p>
      To measure this, we embed each manifesto sentence into the
      same vector space as the party's reservation reasoning during
      the mandate, assign each sentence to one of 28 policy topics
      via cosine similarity, and compare within-topic-within-party
      cells (those with at least five manifesto sentences). Without
      the topic restriction the comparison would mainly measure
      register differences, since cabinet parties write polished
      committee formulations while opposition parties write
      technical reservations. The topic restriction removes most of
      that confound.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/26_topic_matched_gap.png`} alt="Topic-matched stated-vs-revealed gap per party" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-party mean cosine between manifesto and reservation
        language across covered topics, with the number of comparable
        topics in parentheses. Higher = the party speaks more
        similarly in its manifesto as in its parliamentary work.
        KD (n=1) and MP (n=3) have too few topics with sufficient
        manifesto material to interpret reliably; their bars are
        shown but should be read with caution.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The headline pattern, with the small-sample parties set aside,
      is as follows.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>L is the most consistent</strong> (0.76 mean
        across 9 topics). Liberalerna's manifesto language and its
        reservation language describe policy in the same register.
        The L defectors finding above adds a caveat, however: the
        manifesto and the committee work line up, while the floor
        vote of much of the L caucus sits closer to KD and M.</li>
      <li><strong>V has the largest gap</strong> (0.61 across 11
        topics). Vänsterpartiet's manifesto is aspirational and
        rhetorical, while its reservations are technical legal
        critiques. The within-topic gap is real and structural
        rather than a sample artefact.</li>
      <li><strong>SD is unexpectedly consistent</strong> (0.71
        across 19 topics). A long, technical manifesto and a long
        record of detailed reservation work, written in compatible
        registers up until the election year.</li>
    </ul>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/27_party_topic_gap_matrix.png`} alt="Party by topic gap matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        One cell per (party, topic). Pale cells = the party speaks
        similarly in its manifesto and in its parliamentary work on
        that topic; dark cells = the two diverge. Topics are sorted by
        mean divergence across parties.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The topics that diverge most across parties are civil emergency
      preparedness, industrial policy and health care. The pattern
      is similar in each case: the manifestos describe these as
      questions of resilience, growth and dignity, while the
      reservations describe them as specific clauses, allocations
      and amendments. The topics where the gap is smallest are
      those where the manifestos already wrote in policy-instrument
      language: tax (where manifestos state specific rates),
      defence (where all parties use Nato procurement vocabulary),
      and migration.
    </p>

    <h3>Inside parliament, two registers</h3>

    <p>
      The manifesto is one register. Parliament has two of its own:
      the chamber speech, oral and often delivered without notes,
      and the written reservation, drafted by party staff and
      polished. If a party speaks the same way in both, its
      parliamentary register is internally consistent. If the two
      diverge, the chamber persona and the committee persona differ.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/32_speech_vs_reservation.png`} alt="Per-party speech vs reservation cosine similarity" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-party mean speech reasoning vector against mean reservation
        reasoning vector, restricted to (party, topic) cells covered by
        both. Higher = the party uses the same vocabulary in chamber
        speeches as in written reservations.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The four opposition parties and Sverigedemokraterna all land
      in a tight 0.87 to 0.89 band. Inside parliament, each of these
      five parties speaks the same way regardless of register. The
      cabinet bars are hatched because the cabinet writes almost no
      reservations: L has reservation material in only 8 topic
      cells, KD in 11, M in 8. The bars are technically computable
      but the sample is too small to treat as a finding.
    </p>

    <p>
      The opposition's internal consistency matters for the
      interpretation of an earlier result. The largest
      manifesto-versus-reservation gap is Vänsterpartiet's, but
      this is not because V is register-inconsistent inside
      parliament. V's chamber speech and its written reservations
      track each other closely. The gap is therefore between V's
      manifesto and its parliamentary work as a whole, and not
      between two registers of parliamentary work.
    </p>

    <h2>For a 2026 voter</h2>

    <p>
      This article describes the Riksdag. It does not score parties
      against each other, and it does not recommend a vote. What it
      can offer a voter is a way to route by issue, a structured
      question about which document to trust, and an account of
      what the data cannot answer.
    </p>

    <h3>Where does your priority issue live?</h3>

    <p>
      Topics differ enormously in how much they separate parties.
      The per-topic figure earlier in the article allows a voter to
      route by issue.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Migration.</strong> The sharpest split in the
        chamber. V, MP and C on one side, M, KD, L and SD on the
        other, with Socialdemokraterna in between. If migration is
        the decisive issue for a voter, the side of the bloc line
        determines the outcome, while within-side party choice
        changes little.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>International aid (bistånd).</strong> The same
        4-vs-4 alignment as migration, with no within-bloc nuance.
        The opposition defends the budget, while the cabinet and
        SD cut it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Climate.</strong> V and MP are the distinctive
        pro-climate voices (klimat is MP's signature value), and
        SD is the distinctive outlier on the other side. The
        cabinet trio is mixed. For climate as the decisive issue,
        V or MP carries the most distinctive vote.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Schools, pharmaceuticals, dental care.</strong>
        Welfare-expansion topics. The opposition is in favour and
        the cabinet plus SD against. The cluster pattern matches
        migration.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Other topics.</strong> Cross-party variance drops
        sharply outside the top five most polarising topics. If a
        voter's decisive issue is not on that polarising list, the
        four-year record suggests that party choice will affect
        that issue less than other criteria might.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Which document do you trust?</h3>

    <p>
      A manifesto is a document a party writes ahead of an
      election, with no immediate obligation to act on its content.
      The parliamentary record is the document of what the party
      actually does once elected. For several parties in this
      dataset the two diverge in different ways. Vänsterpartiet's
      manifesto is the most aspirational of the eight, while its
      reservations are the most technical; a voter who weights
      aspirational language heavily will find the V manifesto
      setting an expectation that the V record then undershoots.
      Liberalerna's manifesto and committee work line up closely,
      while the floor votes of a substantial share of the L caucus
      sit nearer to Kristdemokraterna and Moderaterna than to the
      L manifesto. The four Tidö manifestos each promise something
      distinctive in 2022, while the chamber record of the mandate
      collapses those distinct promises into a single voting bloc.
      Each of these mismatches is worth knowing before weighting
      one document above the other.
    </p>

    <h3>Does silence in a manifesto count against a party?</h3>

    <p>
      Kristdemokraterna's 1,600-word manifesto registers meaningful
      content in 1 of 28 policy topics, while Sverigedemokraterna's
      21,000-word manifesto covers 19. When a party does not write
      about an issue that a voter cares about, that may indicate
      that they accept the prevailing consensus, that they have
      not formed a position, or that they would prefer to be
      evaluated on something else. The analysis cannot distinguish
      between these interpretations; that distinction is the
      voter's to draw.
    </p>

    <h3>What the data cannot answer</h3>

    <p>
      Two questions sit outside the chamber record entirely. The
      first is whether the Tidö fusion should be read as
      responsible coalition support or as the absorption of a
      fourth party into a three-party cabinet without the public
      accountability of a cabinet seat. The data establishes that
      the fusion is real, structural and asymmetric, in the sense
      that Sverigedemokraterna moved toward the cabinet rather
      than the cabinet adjusting toward SD; how that movement is
      interpreted is a question for the reader. The second is
      whether the pattern of this mandate will continue, reverse
      or splinter in the years after the 2026 election. This
      article is based on the closed four-year period of the
      2022-26 mandate, and behaviour in the next mandate must be
      read from data that is not yet available.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <p class="method-note">
      All analysis is based on reproducible methods over public
      data from <a href="https://data.riksdagen.se">data.riksdagen.se</a>
      and the eight 2022 party manifestos from the SND "Vi vill"
      archive. The source code and full method write-up are
      available at <a href="https://github.com/freol35241/ps-sverige">GitHub</a>.
      The analysis uses no interviews and no survey data, and the
      subjective judgements required are limited to defining keyword
      pools, topic clusters and vocabulary lists, which are
      documented openly in the code.
    </p>
  </article>

  <article class="container companion-article">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Companion analysis · The first 2026 manifesto</p>
      <h1>Liberalerna 2022 to 2026: a three-layer comparison</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Of the eight parties on the 2026 ballot, only Liberalerna has
        so far published a finalised election manifesto. This
        companion piece runs the three-layer comparison (2022
        manifesto, 2022-26 chamber record, 2026 manifesto) for the
        one party where all three documents currently exist.
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      The main article analysed the eight parties at the level of
      their 2022 manifestos and their 2022-26 chamber record. With
      the September 2026 election three months away, the natural
      next question is what each party now says about its own record
      in its 2026 manifesto. A scoping pass of party-website material
      in mid-June found only Liberalerna with a finalised 2026
      valmanifest ("För din frihet", 40 pages, presented 2 June 2026
      by Simona Mohamsson). Vänsterpartiet has a preliminary congress
      platform of around four pages; Socialdemokraterna has a
      three-pillar "Plan för Sverige"; Centerpartiet has a short
      valplan; Miljöpartiet has a draft on the party website that is
      currently password-locked; and Moderaterna, Kristdemokraterna
      and Sverigedemokraterna have nothing publishable beyond
      signalling documents. The full eight-party analysis will
      therefore have to wait for the September manifesto wave,
      typically released four to eight weeks before election day.
      In the meantime, Liberalerna is also the most analytically
      charged single case in the main article: the L-defectors
      finding identified the Liberalerna caucus as the fifth
      behavioural cluster, voting on the floor closer to KD and M
      than to its own party. The 2026 manifesto offers a test of
      how L now writes about that record.
    </p>

    <h2>The manifesto grew, the register shape held</h2>

    <p>
      Liberalerna's 2026 manifesto is the longer of the two by
      roughly 28 percent: 9,452 words against 7,375 in 2022, and 673
      substantive sentences against 469. The proportional share of
      each register moved less than the word count. Diagnosis dropped
      from 6.0 to 4.0 percent of substantive sentences, end-state
      share rose fractionally from 10.4 to 10.8 percent, and
      mechanism share fell from 11.1 to 9.7 percent. L is still a
      manifesto written more in policy detail than in critique or
      vision, and that basic balance survived four years in cabinet.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/40_l_element_shares.png`} alt="Element shares in L's 2022 and 2026 manifestos" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Share of substantive sentences classified into each register
        using the same keyword classifier as the main article.
        Diagnosis, end state and mechanism are the three measurable
        elements; the remainder are classified as "other".
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>The value vocabulary shifted toward the title</h2>

    <p>
      More movement is visible in the value vocabulary than in the
      register shares. The most striking change is in the value that
      the manifesto's title invokes: mentions of frihet rose from
      2.4 to 6.2 per 1,000 words, more than doubling, and frihet
      becomes the second-most-frequent value in the document.
      Trygghet rose from 2.1 to 3.7 per 1,000 words, tillväxt from
      2.3 to 3.5, and ansvar from 1.3 to 2.4. In the opposite
      direction, klimat fell from 4.0 to 2.3 per 1,000 words and
      demokrati from 2.7 to 1.0. The directional pattern is a shift
      toward a classical-liberal core (frihet, individens, valfrihet)
      reinforced by values previously more strongly associated with
      the cabinet partners (trygghet, ansvar, tillväxt).
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/41_l_signature_values.png`} alt="L's value vocabulary, 2022 vs 2026" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-1,000-word frequency for each value, using the same value
        vocabulary as the main article. Union of the top 10 values
        in each manifesto, sorted left-to-right by 2022 frequency.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      A caveat on the largest bar in the figure. The
      nationell_identitet pattern matches every occurrence of
      "Sverige", "svensk", "nationell" or "identitet", not only
      identity-coded usage. The drop from 15.6 to 11.2 per 1,000
      words is therefore partly a measure of how often the manifesto
      says "Sverige" per word, which a longer and more discursive
      document will mechanically reduce. The frihet, trygghet, klimat
      and demokrati changes use narrower patterns and are more
      interpretable as actual shifts in value emphasis.
    </p>

    <h2>The 2026 manifesto matches the chamber record less closely than the 2022 one</h2>

    <p>
      The main article measured each party's stated-vs-revealed gap
      as the mean cosine similarity between manifesto and reservation
      language across topics covered in both. Liberalerna was the
      most consistent party in that comparison, at 0.76 across nine
      covered topics. Applying the same method to the 2026 manifesto
      gives 0.69 across 13 covered topics.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/42_l_topic_gap_2022_vs_2026.png`} alt="L manifesto vs L chamber, 2022 and 2026" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mean topic-matched cosine between L's manifesto and L's
        reservation reasoning vectors, across covered topics.
        Higher = the two languages describe policy in more similar
        terms.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The two figures are suggestive rather than strictly comparable,
      because the topic sets differ. The 2026 manifesto covers more
      topics than the 2022 one (13 against 9), and some of those
      topics have weaker chamber-record material from L. The drop
      is therefore in part a topic-mix effect. A cleaner test
      follows by comparing the 2026 manifesto to every party's
      chamber reasoning, not only to L's own.
    </p>

    <h2>In 2026 as in 2022, L's manifesto is barely more L than M or S</h2>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/43_l_2026_vs_party_reservations.png`} alt="L's 2026 manifesto cosine against every party's chamber reasoning, with the 2022 comparison" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        For each party, the mean topic-matched cosine between L's
        manifesto and that party's reservation and speech vectors,
        across the topics covered by L's manifesto. Light bars: L
        2022. Dark bars: L 2026. The bordered bar marks the party
        with the highest similarity to L 2026.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Two patterns in the figure deserve attention separately. First,
      the absolute level of similarity is lower in 2026 than in 2022
      across every party comparison. L 2026 sits between 0.64 and
      0.69 against the eight parties, while L 2022 sat between 0.70
      and 0.76. The drop is roughly uniform at about 0.07 across all
      eight parties, including L's own chamber work. The 0.76-to-0.69
      figure above is therefore not a directional drift of L's
      manifesto away from L's chamber record; it is the same uniform
      register shift, restricted to the L row of the matrix. The
      2026 manifesto is written in a register that is less aligned
      with parliamentary reasoning of any party than the 2022
      manifesto was, which is consistent with the life-journey
      framing of "För din frihet" (eight sections organised around
      school, work, family, security, healthcare and freedom).
    </p>

    <p>
      Second, the within-2026 spread between parties is narrow. L
      2026 against L sits at 0.69, against M at 0.68, against S at
      0.68. The same property held in 2022, where L sat at 0.76, M
      at 0.76 and KD at 0.74. Liberalerna writes its election
      material in a register that does not strongly distinguish it
      from its cabinet partners' parliamentary work, and that
      property held across the mandate. For the L-defectors finding
      in the main article, the manifesto layer was always going to
      be a poor place to look for the gap. The gap is between the
      manifesto register and the floor-vote behaviour of the L
      caucus, not between the L manifesto and the M committee
      register, which already overlap closely.
    </p>

    <h2>What this article cannot yet test</h2>

    <p>
      A single-party three-layer comparison is the maximum the
      current public corpus allows. The questions that the main
      article opens up for 2026 mostly need other parties' new
      manifestos. Whether the four Tidö manifestos still keep M,
      KD, L and SD as four separate documents in 2026, or whether
      the chamber-record fusion has bled into the written documents,
      requires all four. Whether the opposition parties' manifestos
      reflect the punishment-vocabulary drift in C and MP that the
      main article documented requires those parties' 2026
      documents. Both questions are scheduled for the September
      manifesto wave, when most of the remaining parties are
      expected to release their election material.
    </p>
  </article>
